    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-05-19T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-05-19T13:00:00-05:00" n="473"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d473">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">357.<gloss target="#t_AC1">AC</gloss>/5–1950:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Douglas</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-05-19T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 19, 1950—7 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2795. <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 2670, May 15.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d473fn1">Not printed: it provided some interim views of Mr. Furlonge
                        on this question (357.<gloss target="#t_AC1">AC</gloss>/5–1550).</note>
                    Furlonge said today that he understood that Drew and Kirkbride had discussed in
                    Amman possibility Jordan negotiating with Israel through <gloss target="#t_PCC1"
                        >PCC</gloss> machinery. Kirkbride has reported that, in view Jordan Cabinet
                    deadlock over question resumption direct negotiations with Israel, it might be
                    good idea for <pb facs="0925" n="903" xml:id="pg_903"/> US and UK to encourage
                    Jordan to accept <gloss target="#t_PCC1">PCC</gloss> offer. Kirkbride
                    emphasized, however, that there should be no pressure on Jordan to accept and
                    that Jordan should not be encouraged to consult with other Arab states on this
                    question. Furlonge said now that <gloss target="#t_AL1">AL</gloss> political
                    commission has adjourned, Foreign Office concurs Kirkbride’s line and is
                    prepared join with US in giving appropriate encouragement to Jordan.</p>
                <p>From remarks which Furlonge dropped, we gather Foreign Office is not at all
                    optimistic re possibility Jordan reaching settlement with Israel through <gloss
                        target="#t_PCC1">PCC</gloss> machinery. Foreign Office’s principal interest
                    in proposal seems to lie in fact that its acceptance would result in
                    reconciliation differences between Abdullah and his Cabinet.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 2795; repeated information Geneva 74.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Douglas</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
